function monotoneIncreasingDigits(n) {
    let n_str = n.toString();
    let n_len = n_str.length;

    let i = n_len - 1;
    while (i > 0) {
        if (n_str.charAt(i) < n_str.charAt(i - 1)) {
            n_str = n_str.slice(0, i-1) + String.fromCharCode(n_str.charCodeAt(i-1) - 1) + '9'.repeat(n_len - i);
        }
        --i;
    }

    return parseInt(n_str);
}
```


    1. Convert the input integer to a string for easier manipulation of individual digits, and get its length.
2. Initialize counter `i` starting at the right-most digit and going left.
3. If the current digit is less than the previous one, we decrement the previous digit by 1 as it must be less than or equal, then set all digits to the right of the modified digit to 9 (so that the number remains the largest possible).
4. Continue with step 3 until every previous digit has been checked, adjusting digits as needed.
5. Convert the string of digits back to an integer and return it.

solutionCode.java:
    ```java
public int monotoneIncreasingDigits(int n) {
    char[] n_str = String.valueOf(n).toCharArray();
    int n_len = n_str.length;

    int i = n_len - 1;
    while (i > 0) {
        if (n_str[i] < n_str[i - 1]) {
            n_str[i - 1] -= 1;
            for (int j = i; j < n_len; ++j) {
                n_str[j] = '9';
            }
        }
        --i;
    }

    return Integer.parseInt(new String(n_str));
}
```

    1. Convert the input integer to a string for easier manipulation of individual digits, and get its length.
2. Initialize counter `i` starting at the right-most digit and going left.
3. If the current digit is less than the previous one, we decrement the previous digit by 1 as it must be less than or equal, then set all digits to the right of the modified digit to 9 (so that the number remains the largest possible).
4. Continue with step 3 until every previous digit has been checked, adjusting digits as needed.
5. Convert the string of digits back to an integer and return it.
